Figure 2.14 illustrates an example of an emitter follower. This name is derived from the fact that the output terminal is the emitter, which closely follows the input (the base), minus one diode drop:

$$
V_{E} \approx V_{B} - 0.6 \text{ volts.}
$$

The output is essentially a copy of the input, but 0.6 to 0.7 V less positive. For this circuit, $V_{\text{in}}$ must remain at or above +0.6 V; otherwise, the output will be at ground level. By connecting the emitter resistor to a negative supply voltage, negative voltage swings can also be allowed. It is important to note that there is no collector resistor in an emitter follower.
