extrainfo: The circuit is configured as an emitter follower. It exhibits high input impedance and low output impedance, with a voltage gain of approximately 1. The output voltage is a slightly diminished replica of the input voltage, reduced by the base-emitter voltage drop (~0.6-0.7V).

Figure 2.14. Emitter follower.

Initially, this circuit might seem largely ineffective. However, its utility becomes apparent when you recognize that the input impedance is significantly higher than the output impedance, a point that will be demonstrated shortly. This characteristic means the circuit demands less power from the signal source to drive a given load compared to if the signal source were to drive the load directly. Additionally, a signal with some internal impedance (in the Thvenin sense) can now drive a load of similar or even lower impedance without amplitude loss (typically caused by the voltage-divider effect). In essence, an emitter follower provides current gain, despite lacking voltage gain. It possesses power gain. Voltage gain is not the sole measure of a circuit's effectiveness!

