Exercise 2.5. Utilize a follower with the base driven from a voltage divider to create a stable +5V source from an available regulated +15V supply. The load current $(\max)$ is 25 mA. Select resistor values such that the output voltage does not drop more than 5% under full load.

The simplest regulated voltage supply is just a zener (Figure 2.20). A certain current must pass through the zener, so you select

$$
\frac{V_{\mathrm{in}}(\min )-V_{\text {out }}}{R}>I_{\mathrm{out}}(\max ) .
$$

Since $V_{\text {in }}$ is unregulated, you use the lowest possible $V_{\text {in }}$ value. Designing for optimal operation under the worst conditions (minimum $V_{\text {in }}$ and maximum $I_{\text {out }}$) is termed "worst-case" design. In practice, you also consider component tolerances, line voltage limits, etc., to accommodate the most severe possible combination.

