Figure 2.20. Simple zener voltage regulator.

The zener must be capable of dissipating

$$
P_{\text {zener }}=\left(\frac{V_{\mathrm{in}}-V_{\mathrm{out}}}{R}-I_{\mathrm{out}}\right) V_{\text {zener }}
$$

Again, for worst-case design, you would use $V_{\text {in }}(\max )$ and $I_{\text {out }}$ (min).

Exercise 2.6. Design a +10 V regulated supply for load currents ranging from 0 to 100 mA; the input voltage varies from +20 to +25 V. Ensure at least 10 mA zener current under all (worst-case) conditions. What power rating is required for the zener?

This basic zener-regulated supply is occasionally used for noncritical circuits or those with low current requirements. However, its utility is limited due to several factors:

- $V_{\text {out }}$ cannot be adjusted or precisely set.
- Zener diodes offer only moderate ripple rejection and regulation against input or load changes, due to their finite dynamic impedance.
- For widely varying load currents, a high-power zener is often needed to manage dissipation at low load currents. ${ }^{16}$

By incorporating an emitter follower to isolate the zener, you achieve the improved circuit shown in Figure 2.21. This setup significantly enhances performance. Zener current can be made largely independent of load current, as the transistor base current is minimal, and much lower zener power dissipation is achievable (reduced by up to a factor of $\beta$). The collector resistor $R_{\mathrm{C}}$ can be added to protect the transistor from temporary output short circuits by limiting the current, even though it is not essential to the emitter follower's function. Choose $R_{\mathrm{C}}$ so that its voltage drop is less than that across $R$ for the highest normal load current (i.e., to prevent transistor saturation at maximum load).

