Figure 2.23. Biasing an emitter follower from a previous stage.

The most basic regulated voltage supply is a simple zener diode (Figure 2.20). For the zener to function, a certain current must pass through it, so you select

$$
\frac{V_{\mathrm{in}}(\min )-V_{\text {out }}}{R}>I_{\mathrm{out}}(\max ) .
$$

Since $V_{\text {in }}$ is unregulated, you use the lowest possible $V_{\text {in }}$ value that might occur. Designing for optimal performance under the worst-case scenario (minimum $V_{\text {in }}$ and maximum $I_{\text {out }}$) is termed "worst-case" design. In reality, you must also consider component tolerances, line voltage variations, etc., to ensure the design accommodates the most adverse combination of conditions.

