The zener must be capable of dissipating

$$
P_{\text {zener }}=\left(\frac{V_{\mathrm{in}}-V_{\mathrm{out}}}{R}-I_{\mathrm{out}}\right) V_{\text {zener }}
$$

For worst-case design, you would use $V_{\text {in }}(\max )$ and $I_{\text {out }}(\min )$.

Exercise 2.6. Design a +10 V regulated supply for load currents ranging from 0 to 100 mA; the input voltage varies from +20 to +25 V. Ensure at least 10 mA zener current under all (worst-case) conditions. Determine the required power rating for the zener.

This straightforward zener-regulated supply is occasionally used for noncritical circuits or those with minimal current requirements. However, its utility is limited due to several factors:

- $V_{\text {out }}$ cannot be adjusted or precisely set.
- Zener diodes offer only moderate ripple rejection and regulation against input or load changes, due to their finite dynamic impedance.
- For load currents that vary widely, a high-power zener is often needed to manage dissipation at low load currents. ${ }^{16}$

By incorporating an emitter follower to isolate the zener, you achieve the enhanced circuit shown in Figure 2.21. This setup significantly improves performance. Zener current can be made largely independent of load current, as the transistor base current is minimal, and zener power dissipation can be substantially reduced (by up to a factor of $\beta$). The collector resistor $R_{\mathrm{C}}$ can be added to protect the transistor from temporary output short circuits by limiting the current, although it is not crucial for the emitter follower's function. Choose $R_{\mathrm{C}}$ such that its voltage drop is less than that across $R$ for the highest normal load current (i.e., to prevent transistor saturation at maximum load).

