When an emitter follower is driven from a preceding stage in a circuit, it is generally acceptable to connect its base directly to the previous stage's output, as depicted in Figure 2.23.

[^60]Since the signal on $Q_{1}$'s collector always remains within the power supply range, $Q_{2}$'s base will be between $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$ and ground, ensuring $Q_{2}$ operates in the active region (neither cut off nor saturated). In this state, its base-emitter diode conducts, and its collector voltage stays at least a few tenths of a volt above its emitter. However, the input to a follower may not always be conveniently positioned relative to the supply voltages. A common scenario is a capacitively coupled (or AC-coupled) signal from an external source, such as an audio signal input to a stereo amplifier. In such cases, the signal's average voltage is zero, and direct coupling to an emitter follower results in an output like that shown in Figure 2.24.

