extrainfo:This circuit is an AC-coupled emitter follower designed for audio signals ranging from 20 Hz to 20 kHz. The power supply voltage is 15 V, and the quiescent current is 1 mA. The emitter voltage is set to 7.5 V for maximum symmetrical swing.

Figure 2.25. An AC-coupled emitter follower. Note the base bias voltage divider.

#### A. Emitter Follower Design Example

For a practical design example, let's create an emitter follower for audio signals (20 Hz to 20 kHz). $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$ is +15 V, and the quiescent current is set to 1 mA.

Step 1. Select $V_{E}$. For the largest possible symmetrical swing without clipping, $V_{E}=0.5 V_{\mathrm{CC}}$, or +7.5 volts.

Step 2. Choose $R_{\mathrm{E}}$. For a quiescent current of 1 mA, $R_{\mathrm{E}}=7.5 \mathrm{k}$.

Step 3. Determine $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$. $V_{\mathrm{B}}$ is $V_{\mathrm{E}}+0.6 \mathrm{~V}$, or 8.1 V. This sets the ratio of $R_{1}$ to $R_{2}$ as 1:1.17. The loading criterion requires that the parallel resistance of $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ be around 75 k or less (one-tenth of $7.5 \mathrm{k} \times \beta$). Suitable standard values are $R_{1}=130 \mathrm{k}$, $R_{2}=150 \mathrm{k}$.

Step 4. Choose $C_{1}$. The capacitor $C_{1}$ forms a high-pass filter with the impedance it sees as a load, namely the impedance looking into the base in parallel with the impedance looking into the base voltage divider. Assuming the load this circuit will drive is large compared to the emitter resistor, the impedance looking into the base is $\beta R_{\mathrm{E}}$, about 750 k. The divider appears as 70 k. Thus, the capacitor sees a load of approximately 63 k and should be at least $0.15 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ to ensure the 3 dB point is below the lowest frequency of interest, 20 Hz.

Step 5. Select $C_{2}$. The capacitor $C_{2}$ forms a high-pass filter with the load impedance, which is unknown. However, it is safe to assume the load impedance will not be smaller than $R_{\mathrm{E}}$. This results in a value for $C_{2}$ of at least $1.0 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ to place the 3 dB point below 20 Hz. Due to the presence of two cascaded high-pass filter sections, the capacitor values should be increased slightly to prevent excessive attenuation (a reduction of signal amplitude, in this case 6 dB) at the lowest frequency of interest. $C_{1}=0.47 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ and $C_{2}=3.3 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ might be appropriate choices. ${ }^{18}$

[^61]From our simplified transistor model, the output impedance at the emitter is $\mathbf{Z}_{\text {out }}=R_{\mathrm{E}} \|\left[\left(\mathbf{Z}_{\text {in }}\left\|R_{1}\right\| R_{2}\right) / \beta\right]$, where $\mathbf{Z}_{\text {in }}$ is the (Thvenin) output resistance of the signal driving this circuit. Assuming $\beta \approx 100$, a signal source with $10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$ output resistance would result in an output impedance (at the emitter) of about $87 \Omega$. As discussed later in the chapter (2.3), an additional resistance, the intrinsic emitter impedance $r_{\mathrm{e}}$, effectively in series with the emitter, adds $0.025 / I_{\mathrm{E}}$. Thus, the output impedance here (with a $10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$ source) would be approximately $110 \Omega$.

#### B. Followers with Split Supplies

Since signals often hover "near ground," it is advantageous to use symmetrical positive and negative supplies. This simplifies biasing and eliminates the need for coupling capacitors (Figure 2.26).
Warning: Always ensure a DC path for base bias current, even if it only goes to ground. In this circuit, it is assumed that the signal source has a DC path to ground. If not (e.g., if the signal is capacitively coupled), a resistor to ground must be provided (Figure 2.27). $R_{\mathrm{B}}$ could be about one-tenth of $\beta R_{\mathrm{E}}$, as previously discussed.

Exercise 2.8. Design an emitter follower with $\pm 15 \mathrm{~V}$ supplies for operation over the audio range (20 Hz to 20 kHz). Use a 5 mA quiescent current and capacitive input coupling.
