#### C. Bad Biasing

Occasionally, you may encounter poorly designed circuits like the one shown in Figure 2.28. The designer chose $R_{\mathrm{B}}$ based on a specific beta value (100), estimated the base current, and hoped for a 7 V drop across $R_{\mathrm{B}}$. This is a flawed approach; beta is not a reliable parameter and varies significantly. By using voltage biasing with a stable voltage divider, as detailed earlier, the quiescent point becomes insensitive to variations in transistor beta. For example, in the previous design, the emitter voltage would only increase by $0.35 \mathrm{~V}(5 \%)$ if the transistor's beta were 200 instead of the nominal 100. As with this emitter follower example, it is easy to fall into similar traps when designing other transistor configurations (notably the common-emitter amplifier, which will be covered later in this chapter).
