#### D. Cancelling the Offset -I

Wouldn't it be ideal if an emitter follower did not introduce an offset of the output signal by the $V_{\mathrm{BE}} \approx 0.6 \mathrm{~V}$ base-emitter drop? Figure 2.29 demonstrates how to cancel the DC offset by cascading a PNP follower (which has a positive $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offset) with an NPN follower (which has a comparable negative $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offset). Here, the circuit is configured with $\pm 10 \mathrm{~V}$ symmetrical split supplies, and equal-value emitter resistors are used to ensure the two transistors have similar quiescent currents for an input signal near 0 V.

This technique is a useful trick to know and can be quite helpful. However, the cancellation is not perfect, as we will discuss later in the chapter ( $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ varies somewhat with collector current and transistor size, 2.3), and again in Chapter 5. But, as we will see in Chapter 4, it is indeed straightforward to create a follower using operational amplifiers with nearly perfect zero offset ( $10 \mu \mathrm{~V}$ or less), offering input impedances in the gigaohms (or more), input currents in the nanoamps (or less), and output impedances measured in fractions of an ohm. Be sure to preview Chapter 4 for more details.
