#### C. Bad biasing

Occasionally, you may encounter poorly designed circuits like the one shown in Figure 2.28. The designer selected $R_{\mathrm{B}}$ by assuming a specific beta value (100), estimating the base current, and hoping for a 7 V drop across $R_{\mathrm{B}}$. This is a flawed approach; beta is not a reliable parameter and varies significantly. By using voltage biasing with a stable voltage divider, as detailed in the earlier example, the quiescent point becomes insensitive to variations in transistor beta. For instance, in the previous design example, the emitter voltage would only increase by $0.35 \mathrm{~V}(5 \%)$ if the transistor's beta were 200 instead of the nominal 100. As with this emitter follower example, it is easy to fall into similar traps when designing other transistor configurations (notably the common-emitter amplifier, which we will cover later in this chapter).
