To ensure the follower (and any transistor amplifier) operates correctly throughout the entire signal swing, it must be properly biased. In this scenario, a voltage divider is the simplest solution (Figure 2.25). $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ are selected to position the base halfway between ground and $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$ when no input signal is present, meaning $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ are approximately equal. The process of establishing the operating voltages in a circuit without applied signals is known as setting the quiescent point. Typically, the quiescent point is chosen to allow the maximum symmetrical signal swing of the output waveform without clipping. What values should $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ have? Applying our general principle ( $\S 1.2 .5 \mathrm{~A}$, $\S 2.2 .3 \mathrm{~A}$ ), we ensure the impedance of the dc bias source (the impedance looking into the voltage divider) is small compared to the load it drives (the dc impedance looking into the base of the follower). Consequently,

$$
R_{1} \| R_{2} \ll \beta R_{\mathrm{E}}
$$

This is roughly equivalent to stating that the current flowing through the voltage divider should be significantly larger than the base current.

