#### C. Bad biasing

Occasionally, you may encounter poorly designed circuits like the one shown in Figure 2.28. The designer chose $R_{\mathrm{B}}$ based on an assumed beta value of 100, estimated the base current, and hoped for a 7 V drop across $R_{\mathrm{B}}$. This is a flawed design; beta is not a reliable parameter and varies significantly. By using voltage biasing with a stable voltage divider, as detailed in the earlier example, the quiescent point becomes insensitive to variations in transistor beta. For instance, in the previous design example, the emitter voltage would only increase by $0.35 \mathrm{~V}(5 \%)$ if the transistor's beta were 200 instead of the nominal 100. As with this emitter follower example, it is easy to fall into similar traps and design suboptimal transistor circuits in other configurations (notably the common-emitter amplifier, which we will cover later in this chapter).
