To ensure the follower (or any transistor amplifier) operates correctly throughout the entire signal swing, it is necessary to bias the circuit appropriately. A voltage divider is the simplest method for achieving this (Figure 2.25). $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ are selected to position the base voltage halfway between ground and $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$ in the absence of an input signal, meaning $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ are approximately equal. Setting the operating voltages in a circuit without applied signals is known as establishing the quiescent point. Typically, the quiescent point is chosen to allow the maximum symmetrical signal swing of the output waveform without clipping. What values should $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ have? Applying our general principle ( $\S 1.2 .5 \mathrm{~A}$, $\S 2.2 .3 \mathrm{~A}$ ), we ensure the impedance of the dc bias source (the impedance looking into the voltage divider) is small compared to the load it drives (the dc impedance looking into the base of the follower). In this scenario,

$$
R_{1} \| R_{2} \ll \beta R_{\mathrm{E}}
$$

This is roughly equivalent to stating that the current flowing through the voltage divider should be significantly larger than the current drawn by the base.
