#### A. Emitter follower design example

As a practical design example, let's create an emitter follower for audio signals (20 Hz to 20 kHz). $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$ is +15 V, and the quiescent current is set to 1 mA.

Step 1. Select $V_{E}$. For the largest possible symmetrical swing without clipping, $V_{E}=0.5 V_{\mathrm{CC}}$, or +7.5 volts.

Step 2. Choose $R_{\mathrm{E}}$. For a quiescent current of 1 mA, $R_{\mathrm{E}}=7.5 \mathrm{k}$.

Step 3. Determine $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$. $V_{\mathrm{B}}$ is $V_{\mathrm{E}}+0.6 \mathrm{~V}$, or 8.1 V. This sets the ratio of $R_{1}$ to $R_{2}$ as 1:1.17. The loading criterion requires that the parallel resistance of $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ be around 75 k or less (one-tenth of $7.5 \mathrm{k} \times \beta$). Suitable standard values are $R_{1}=130 \mathrm{k}$, $R_{2}=150 \mathrm{k}$.

Step 4. Choose $C_{1}$. The capacitor $C_{1}$ forms a highpass filter with the impedance it sees as a load, namely the impedance looking into the base in parallel with the impedance looking into the base voltage divider. Assuming the load this circuit drives is large compared to the emitter resistor, the impedance looking into the base is $\beta R_{\mathrm{E}}$, about 750 k. The divider impedance is 70 k. Thus, the capacitor sees a load of approximately 63 k, and it should have a value of at least $0.15 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ to ensure the 3 dB point is below the lowest frequency of interest, 20 Hz.

Step 5. Select $C_{2}$. The capacitor $C_{2}$ forms a highpass filter with the load impedance, which is unknown. However, it is safe to assume the load impedance will not be smaller than $R_{\mathrm{E}}$. This results in a value for $C_{2}$ of at least $1.0 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ to place the 3 dB point below 20 Hz. Since there are two cascaded highpass filter sections, the capacitor values should be increased slightly to prevent excessive attenuation (a reduction of signal amplitude, in this case 6 dB) at the lowest frequency of interest. $C_{1}=0.47 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ and $C_{2}=3.3 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ might be appropriate choices. ${ }^{18}$

[^61]From our simple transistor model, the output impedance at the emitter is $\mathbf{Z}_{\text {out }}=R_{\mathrm{E}} \|\left[\left(\mathbf{Z}_{\text {in }}\left\|R_{1}\right\| R_{2}\right) / \beta\right]$, where $\mathbf{Z}_{\text {in }}$ is the (Thvenin) output resistance of the signal driving the circuit. With $\beta \approx 100$, a signal source with $10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$ output resistance would result in an output impedance (at the emitter) of about $87 \Omega$. As we will discuss later in the chapter (2.3), an additional resistance, the intrinsic emitter impedance $r_{\mathrm{e}}$, effectively in series with the emitter, adds $0.025 / I_{\mathrm{E}}$. Thus, the output impedance here (with a $10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$ source) would be approximately $110 \Omega$.

