#### C. Bad biasing

Occasionally, one encounters poorly designed circuits like the one depicted in Figure 2.28. The designer chose $R_{\mathrm{B}}$ based on an assumed beta value (100), estimated the base current, and hoped for a 7 V drop across $R_{\mathrm{B}}$. This is a flawed approach; beta is not a reliable parameter and varies significantly. By using voltage biasing with a stable voltage divider, as detailed in the earlier example, the quiescent point becomes insensitive to variations in transistor beta. For instance, in the previous design example, the emitter voltage would only increase by $0.35 \mathrm{~V}(5 \%)$ if the transistor's beta were 200 instead of the nominal 100. As with this emitter follower example, it is easy to fall into similar traps when designing other transistor circuits, notably the common-emitter amplifier, which will be discussed later in this chapter.
