To ensure the follower (or any transistor amplifier) operates correctly throughout the entire signal swing, it must be properly biased. In this scenario, a voltage divider is the simplest method (Figure 2.25). $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ are selected to position the base halfway between ground and $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$ in the absence of an input signal, meaning $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ are roughly equal. The process of setting the operating voltages in a circuit without applied signals is known as establishing the quiescent point. Typically, the quiescent point is chosen to allow the maximum symmetrical signal swing of the output waveform without clipping (flattening of the waveform's top or bottom). What values should $R_{1}$ and $R_{2}$ have? Applying our general principle ( $\S 1.2 .5 \mathrm{~A}$, $\S 2.2 .3 \mathrm{~A}$ ), we ensure the impedance of the dc bias source (the impedance looking into the voltage divider) is small compared to the load it drives (the dc impedance looking into the base of the follower). In this case,

$$
R_{1} \| R_{2} \ll \beta R_{\mathrm{E}}
$$

This is approximately equivalent to stating that the current flowing through the voltage divider should be significantly larger than the current drawn by the base.
