#### C. Bad biasing

Occasionally, you may encounter poorly designed circuits like the one shown in Figure 2.28. The designer chose $R_{\mathrm{B}}$ based on a specific beta value (100), estimated the base current, and hoped for a 7 V drop across $R_{\mathrm{B}}$. This is a flawed design; beta is not a reliable parameter and varies significantly. By using voltage biasing with a stable voltage divider, as detailed earlier, the quiescent point becomes insensitive to transistor beta variations. For example, in the previous design example, the emitter voltage would only increase by $0.35 \mathrm{~V}(5 \%)$ if the transistor's beta were 200 instead of the nominal 100. As with this emitter follower example, it is equally easy to fall into this trap and design suboptimal transistor circuits in other configurations (notably the common-emitter amplifier, which we will cover later in this chapter).
