#### D. Cancelling the offset -I

Wouldn't it be ideal if an emitter follower did not introduce an offset of the output signal by the $V_{\mathrm{BE}} \approx 0.6 \mathrm{~V}$ base-emitter drop? Figure 2.29 demonstrates how to mitigate the dc offset by cascading a pnp follower (which has a positive $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offset) with an npn follower (which has a comparable negative $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offset). Here, the circuit is configured with $\pm 10 \mathrm{~V}$ symmetrical split supplies, and equal-value emitter resistors are used to ensure the two transistors have similar quiescent currents for an input signal near 0 V.

This technique is a useful trick to know, often providing significant benefits. However, the cancellation is not perfect, due to factors we'll explore later in the chapter ($V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ depends somewhat on collector current and transistor size, 2.3), and further discussed in Chapter 5. But, as we'll see in Chapter 4, it is indeed quite straightforward to create a follower using operational amplifiers with nearly perfect zero offset ($10 \mu \mathrm{~V}$ or less), offering input impedances in the gigaohms (or more), input currents in the nanoamps (or less), and output impedances measured in fractions of an ohm. Look ahead to Chapter 4 for more details.
