Step 5. Choose $C_{2}$. The capacitor $C_{2}$ forms a high-pass filter with the load impedance, which is unknown. However, it is safe to assume the load impedance will not be smaller than $R_{\mathrm{E}}$. This results in a value for $C_{2}$ of at least $1.0 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ to place the 3 dB point below 20 Hz. Due to the presence of two cascaded high-pass filter sections, the capacitor values should be increased slightly to prevent excessive attenuation (reduction of signal amplitude, in this case 6 dB) at the lowest frequency of interest. $C_{1}=0.47 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ and $C_{2}=3.3 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ might be appropriate choices. ${ }^{18}$

[^61]From our simplified transistor model, the output impedance at the emitter is given by $\mathbf{Z}_{\text {out }}=R_{\mathrm{E}} \|\left[\left(\mathbf{Z}_{\text {in }}\left\|R_{1}\right\| R_{2}\right) / \beta\right]$, where $\mathbf{Z}_{\text {in }}$ is the (Thvenin) output resistance of the signal driving the circuit. Assuming $\beta \approx 100$, a signal source with a $10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$ output resistance would result in an output impedance (at the emitter) of about $87 \Omega$. As we will discuss later in the chapter (2.3), an intrinsic emitter impedance, $r_{\mathrm{e}}$, adds an additional resistance of $0.025 / I_{\mathrm{E}}$ effectively in series with the emitter. Therefore, the output impedance here (with a $10 \mathrm{k} \Omega$ source) would be approximately $110 \Omega$.

#### B. Followers with split supplies

Since signals often hover "near ground," it is convenient to use symmetrical positive and negative supplies. This simplifies biasing and eliminates the need for coupling capacitors (Figure 2.26).
Warning: It is crucial to always provide a DC path for base bias current, even if it only goes to ground. In this circuit, it is assumed that the signal source has a DC path to ground. If not (e.g., if the signal is capacitively coupled), a resistor to ground must be provided (Figure 2.27). $R_{\mathrm{B}}$ could be about one-tenth of $\beta R_{\mathrm{E}}$, as previously discussed.

Exercise 2.8. Design an emitter follower with $\pm 15 \mathrm{~V}$ supplies to operate over the audio range (20 Hz to 20 kHz). Use a 5 mA quiescent current and capacitive input coupling.
