#### D. Cancelling the offset -I

Wouldn't it be ideal if an emitter follower did not introduce an offset of the output signal by the $V_{\mathrm{BE}} \approx 0.6 \mathrm{~V}$ base-emitter drop? Figure 2.29 demonstrates how to counteract the DC offset by cascading a pnp follower (which has a positive $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offset) with an npn follower (which has a comparable negative $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offset). Here, the circuit is configured with $\pm 10 \mathrm{~V}$ symmetrical split supplies, and equal-value emitter resistors are used to ensure the two transistors have similar quiescent currents for an input signal near 0 V.

This technique is a useful trick to know and can be quite helpful. However, the cancellation is not perfect, as we will discuss later in the chapter ( $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ depends somewhat on collector current and transistor size, 2.3), and again in Chapter 5. But, as we will see in Chapter 4, it is indeed straightforward to create a follower using operational amplifiers with nearly perfect zero offset ( $10 \mu \mathrm{~V}$ or less), and as a bonus, you achieve input impedances in the gigaohm range (or higher), input currents in the nanoamp range (or lower), and output impedances measured in fractions of an ohm. Be sure to preview Chapter 4.
