Current sources, despite often being overlooked, are just as crucial and beneficial as voltage sources. They are excellent for biasing transistors and are unparalleled as "active loads" for high-gain amplifier stages and as emitter sources for differential amplifiers. Integrators, sawtooth generators, and ramp generators also rely on current sources. They provide wide-voltage-range pullups within amplifier and regulator circuits. Additionally, there are external applications requiring constant current sources, such as electrophoresis and electrochemistry.

#### A. Resistor plus voltage source

The simplest approximation of a current source is depicted in Figure 2.30. As long as $R_{\text {load }} \ll R$ (meaning $V_{\text {load }} \ll V$), the current remains nearly constant and is approximately

$$
I \approx V / R
$$

The load doesn't have to be resistive. A capacitor will charge at a constant rate, provided $V_{\text {cap }} \ll V$; this corresponds to the initial part of the exponential charging curve of an RC circuit.
