There are several limitations to a simple resistor current source. To create a good approximation of a current source, large voltages and significant power dissipation in the resistor are required. Moreover, the current is not easily programmable, meaning it cannot be readily controlled over a wide range by varying a voltage elsewhere in the circuit.

Exercise 2.9. If you need a current source that remains constant to 1% over a load voltage range of 0 to +10 volts, what voltage source must you use in series with a single resistor?

Exercise 2.10. Suppose you want a 10 mA current in the previous problem. How much power is dissipated in the series resistor? How much reaches the load?

#### B. Transistor current source

Fortunately, a very effective current source can be constructed using a transistor (Figure 2.31). It operates as follows: applying $V_{\mathrm{B}}$ to the base, with $V_{\mathrm{B}}>0.6 \mathrm{~V}$, ensures the emitter is always conducting:

$$
V_{\mathrm{E}}=V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts. }
$$

Thus,

$$
I_{\mathrm{E}}=V_{\mathrm{E}} / R_{\mathrm{E}}=\left(V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts }\right) / R_{\mathrm{E}}
$$

Since $I_{\mathrm{E}} \approx I_{\mathrm{C}}$ for large beta,

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{\mathrm{C}} \approx\left(V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts }\right) / R_{\mathrm{E}}, \tag{2.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

independent of $V_{C}$, provided the transistor is not saturated ( $V_{\mathrm{C}} \gtrsim V_{\mathrm{E}}+0.2$ volts).
