#### C. Current-source biasing

The base voltage can be supplied in various ways. A voltage divider is adequate if it is sufficiently stiff. As before, the criterion is that its impedance should be much lower than the dc impedance looking into the base ( $\beta R_{\mathrm{E}}$ ). Alternatively, a zener diode (or a two-terminal IC reference like the LM385), biased from $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$, or even a few forward-biased diodes ${ }^{19}$ in series from base to the corresponding emitter supply, can be used. Figure 2.32 illustrates some examples. In the last example (Figure 2.32C), a pnp transistor sources current to a load returned to ground. The other examples (using $n p n$ transistors) are more accurately termed current sinks, but the common practice is to refer to them all loosely as "current sources." ${ }^{20}$ In the first circuit, the voltage-divider impedance of $\sim 1.3 \mathrm{k}$ is stiff compared to the impedance looking into the base of about 100 k (for $\beta=100$ ), so any changes in beta with collector voltage will not significantly affect the output current by altering the base voltage. In the other two circuits, the biasing resistors are chosen to provide several milliamps to bring the diodes into conduction.

#### D. Compliance

A current source can deliver constant current to the load only within a specific range of load voltage. To do otherwise would imply infinite power. The voltage range over which a current source operates effectively is termed its output compliance. For the transistor current sources discussed earlier, the compliance is determined by the requirement that the transistors remain in the active region. Thus, in the first circuit, the collector voltage can drop to nearly saturation, perhaps +1.1 V at the collector. The second circuit, with its higher emitter voltage, can sink current down to a collector voltage of about +5.1 V.

In all cases, the collector voltage can vary from near saturation to the supply voltage. For instance, the last circuit can source current to the load for any voltage between zero and about +8.6 V across the load. Indeed, the load might even include its own batteries or power supplies, allowing the collector to exceed the supply voltage (Figure 2.32A,B) or go below ground (Figure 2.32 C ). This is acceptable, but transistor breakdown ( $V_{\mathrm{CE}}$ must not exceed $B V_{\mathrm{CEO}}$, the specified collector-emitter breakdown voltage) and excessive power dissipation (determined by $I_{\mathrm{C}} V_{\mathrm{CE}}$ ) must be monitored. As detailed in $\S \S 3.5 .1 \mathrm{~B}, 3.6 .4 \mathrm{C}$, and 9.4 .2 , additional safe-operating-area constraints apply to power transistors.
Exercise 2.11. You have +5 and +15 V regulated supplies available in a circuit. Design a 5 mA npn current sink using the +5 V to bias the base. What is the output compliance?

