A current source does not necessarily require a fixed voltage at the base. By varying $V_{\mathrm{B}}$, you create a voltage-programmable current source. The input signal swing $v_{\text {in }}$ (where lowercase symbols indicate variations) must remain small enough to prevent the emitter voltage from dropping to zero, ensuring the output current reflects input voltage variations smoothly. The result is a current source with output current variations proportional to input voltage variations, $i_{\text {out }}=v_{\text {in }} / R_{\mathrm{E}}$. This forms the basis of the amplifier discussed next (2.2.7).

#### E. Cancelling the offset - II

A minor drawback of these current source circuits is the need to apply a base voltage offset by $V_{\mathrm{BE}} \approx$ 0.6 V from the voltage desired across the emitter resistor, which sets the output current. This is the same offset issue as with an emitter follower, and the same trick (2.2.5D) can be used to achieve approximate cancellation of the offset when it poses a problem.
