A current source doesn't necessarily require a fixed base voltage. By varying $V_{\mathrm{B}}$, a voltage-programmable current source is created. The input signal swing $v_{\text {in }}$ must remain small enough to prevent the emitter voltage from dropping to zero, ensuring the output current reflects input voltage variations smoothly. This results in a current source where $i_{\text {out }}=v_{\text {in }} / R_{\mathrm{E}}$, forming the basis of the amplifier discussed next (2.2.7).

#### E. Cancelling the Offset - II

A minor drawback of these current source circuits is the need for a base voltage offset by $V_{\mathrm{BE}} \approx 0.6 V$ from the desired voltage across the emitter resistor, which sets the output current. This is similar to the offset issue in an emitter follower, and the same trick (2.2.5D) can be used for approximate cancellation in problematic situations.

