In Figure 2.33, the standard current-source output stage $Q_{2}$ sets the current via the voltage across the emitter resistor: $I_{L}=V_{\mathrm{E}} / R_{2}$. Thus, $Q_{2}$'s base needs to be a $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ higher, which the pnp input follower provides. Consequently, the voltage at $Q_{2}$'s emitter closely matches $V_{\text {in }}$, making the output current $I_{\mathrm{L}}=V_{\text {in }} / R_{2}$, free from $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offsets. Ingenious!

However, this cancellation isn't perfectly accurate due to potential differences in the base-emitter drops of the two transistors (2.3). Nevertheless, it's a useful approximation and significantly better than no compensation. The precision of operational amplifiers (Chapter 4) will later provide a more accurate method for creating current sources without the nuisance of $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offsets.

#### F. Deficiencies of Current Sources

While these transistor current-source circuits perform well, they aren't perfect. When scrutinized closely, the load current shows some variation with voltage, indicating a finite Thvenin equivalent resistance ($R_{\mathrm{Th}}<\infty$). The causes of these deficiencies and innovative circuit solutions are discussed later in this chapter and in Chapter 2x.

Current sources, frequently overlooked, are just as crucial and functional as voltage sources. They are exceptional for biasing transistors and unparalleled as "active loads" for high-gain amplifier stages and as emitter sources for differential amplifiers. Devices like integrators, sawtooth generators, and ramp generators rely on current sources. These sources also provide wide-voltage-range pullups in amplifier and regulator circuits. Additionally, there are external applications requiring constant current sources, such as electrophoresis and electrochemistry.

#### A. Resistor plus voltage source

The simplest method to approximate a current source is depicted in Figure 2.30. If $R_{\text {load }} \ll R$ (i.e., $V_{\text {load }} \ll V$), the current remains nearly constant, approximately:

$$
I \approx V / R
$$

The load need not be resistive. A capacitor charges at a constant rate provided $V_{\text {cap }} \ll V$, corresponding to the initial part of an RC exponential charging curve.
