#### B. Transistor current source

Fortunately, a transistor can create an excellent current source (Figure 2.31). By applying $V_{\mathrm{B}}$ to the base, with $V_{\mathrm{B}}>0.6 \mathrm{~V}$, the emitter conducts consistently:

$$
V_{\mathrm{E}}=V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts. }
$$

Thus,

$$
I_{\mathrm{E}}=V_{\mathrm{E}} / R_{\mathrm{E}}=\left(V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts }\right) / R_{\mathrm{E}}
$$

For large beta, where $I_{\mathrm{E}} \approx I_{\mathrm{C}}$,

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{\mathrm{C}} \approx\left(V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts }\right) / R_{\mathrm{E}}, \tag{2.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

independent of $V_{C}$, provided the transistor isn't saturated ($V_{\mathrm{C}} \gtrsim V_{\mathrm{E}}+0.2$ volts).
