The base voltage can be supplied in various ways. A voltage divider is adequate if it is sufficiently stiff. As before, the criterion is that its impedance should be much lower than the dc impedance looking into the base ($\beta R_{\mathrm{E}}$). Alternatively, a zener diode (or a two-terminal IC reference like the LM385), biased from $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$, or even a few forward-biased diodes ${}^{19}$ in series from base to the corresponding emitter supply, can be used. Figure 2.32 illustrates some examples. In the last example (Figure 2.32C), a pnp transistor sources current to a load returned to ground. The other examples (using npn transistors) should technically be called current sinks, but the common practice is to refer to them all loosely as "current sources." ${}^{20}$ In the first circuit, the voltage-divider impedance of $\sim 1.3 \mathrm{k}$ is stiff compared to the impedance looking into the base of about 100 k (for $\beta=100$), so any changes in beta with collector voltage will not significantly affect the output current by altering the base voltage. In the other two circuits, the biasing resistors are chosen to provide several milliamps to bring the diodes into conduction.

