A current source can maintain constant current to the load only within a specific load voltage range. Exceeding this would imply infinite power. The voltage range over which a current source functions effectively is termed its output compliance. For the transistor current sources discussed, compliance is determined by the requirement that transistors remain in the active region. In the first circuit, the collector voltage can drop to near saturation, perhaps +1.1 V. The second circuit, with a higher emitter voltage, can sink current down to a collector voltage of about +5.1 V.

In all cases, the collector voltage can vary from near saturation to the supply voltage. For instance, the last circuit can source current for any voltage between zero and about +8.6 V across the load. The load might even include its own batteries or power supplies, potentially taking the collector beyond the supply voltage (Figure 2.32A,B) or below ground (Figure 2.32C). However, transistor breakdown ( $V_{\mathrm{CE}}$ must not exceed $B V_{\mathrm{CEO}}$) and excessive power dissipation (set by $I_{\mathrm{C}} V_{\mathrm{CE}}$) must be monitored. As detailed in $\S \S 3.5 .1 \mathrm{~B}, 3.6 .4 \mathrm{C}$, and 9.4 .2, additional safe-operating-area constraints apply to power transistors.
Exercise 2.11. With +5 and +15 V regulated supplies available, design a 5 mA npn current sink using the +5 V to bias the base. What is the output compliance?

