Consider Figure 2.33. It features our standard current-source output stage $Q_{2}$, with the current set by the voltage across the emitter resistor: $I_{L}=V_{\mathrm{E}} / R_{2}$. Thus, $Q_{2}$'s base needs to be a $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ higher (the offset), but this is precisely what the pnp input follower accomplishes. Consequently, the voltage at $Q_{2}$'s emitter closely matches $V_{\text {in }}$ applied, and the output current is simply $I_{\mathrm{L}}=V_{\text {in }} / R_{2}$, with no $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offset. Ingenious!

However, this is not a highly accurate cancellation, as the two transistors will generally have different collector currents and thus slightly different base-emitter drops (2.3). Nevertheless, it is a useful first-order approximation and significantly better than no compensation. As discussed in Chapter 4, operational amplifiers offer a more precise method to create current sources where the output current is accurately programmed by an input voltage, without the nuisance of the $V_{\mathrm{BE}}$ offset.

#### F. Deficiencies of current sources

While these transistor current-source circuits perform well, particularly compared to a simple resistor biased from a fixed voltage (Figure 2.30), they are not perfect. Upon closer examination, it becomes evident that the load current exhibits some (relatively small) variation with voltage. Another way to express this is that the current source has a finite $\left(R_{\mathrm{Th}}<\infty\right)$ Thvenin equivalent resistance.

The causes of these deficiencies and some ingenious circuit solutions are discussed later in the chapter and in Chapter 2x.

Current sources, often overlooked, are just as crucial and beneficial as voltage sources. They are excellent for biasing transistors and are unparalleled as "active loads" for high-gain amplifier stages and as emitter sources for differential amplifiers. Devices like integrators, sawtooth generators, and ramp generators rely on current sources. They also provide wide-voltage-range pullups in amplifier and regulator circuits. Additionally, there are external applications requiring constant current sources, such as electrophoresis and electrochemistry.

#### A. Resistor plus voltage source

The simplest approximation of a current source is depicted in Figure 2.30. As long as $R_{\text {load }} \ll R$ (meaning $V_{\text {load }} \ll V$), the current remains nearly constant, approximately:

$$
I \approx V / R
$$

The load need not be resistive. A capacitor will charge at a constant rate, provided $V_{\text {cap }} \ll V$, which corresponds to the initial part of an RC exponential charging curve.
