Figure 2.30. Current-source approximation.
There are several limitations to a simple resistor current source. To approximate a current source effectively, large voltages and significant power dissipation in the resistor are required. Moreover, the current is not easily programmable, i.e., controllable over a wide range via a voltage elsewhere in the circuit.

Exercise 2.9. If you need a current source constant to $1 \%$ over a load voltage range of 0 to +10 volts, what voltage source must you use in series with a single resistor?

Exercise 2.10. Suppose you need a 10 mA current in the previous problem. How much power is dissipated in the series resistor? How much reaches the load?

#### B. Transistor current source

Fortunately, a transistor can be used to create an excellent current source (Figure 2.31). It operates as follows: applying $V_{\mathrm{B}}$ to the base, with $V_{\mathrm{B}}>0.6 \mathrm{~V}$, ensures the emitter is always conducting:

$$
V_{\mathrm{E}}=V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts. }
$$

Thus,

$$
I_{\mathrm{E}}=V_{\mathrm{E}} / R_{\mathrm{E}}=\left(V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts }\right) / R_{\mathrm{E}}
$$

Since $I_{\mathrm{E}} \approx I_{\mathrm{C}}$ for large beta,

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{\mathrm{C}} \approx\left(V_{\mathrm{B}}-0.6 \text { volts }\right) / R_{\mathrm{E}}, \tag{2.5}
\end{equation*}
$$

independent of $V_{C}$, provided the transistor is not saturated ($V_{\mathrm{C}} \gtrsim V_{\mathrm{E}}+0.2$ volts).
