Figure 2.35. The blocking capacitor $C$ is selected so that all relevant frequencies are passed by the high-pass filter it forms with the parallel resistance of the base biasing resistors ${ }^{21}$; specifically,

$$
C \geq \frac{1}{2 \pi f\left(R_{1} \| R_{2}\right)}
$$

The quiescent collector current is 1.0 mA due to the applied base bias and the 1.0 k emitter resistor. This current sets the collector voltage at +10 volts (+20 V minus 1.0 mA through 10 k). Now, consider an applied fluctuation in base voltage $v_{\mathrm{B}}$. The emitter follows with $v_{\mathrm{E}} = v_{\mathrm{B}}$, leading to a fluctuation in emitter current

$$
i_{\mathrm{E}} = v_{\mathrm{E}} / R_{\mathrm{E}} = v_{\mathrm{B}} / R_{\mathrm{E}}
$$

and a nearly identical change in collector current (since $\beta$ is large). Thus, the initial base voltage fluctuation results in a collector voltage fluctuation

$$
v_{\mathrm{C}} = -i_{\mathrm{C}} R_{\mathrm{C}} = -v_{\mathrm{B}}\left(R_{\mathrm{C}} / R_{\mathrm{E}}\right)
$$

Eureka! It's a voltage amplifier, with a voltage gain given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
\text{gain} = v_{\text{out}} / v_{\mathrm{in}} = -R_{\mathrm{C}} / R_{\mathrm{E}} \tag{2.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

In this scenario, the gain is $-10,000 / 1000$, or -10. The negative sign indicates that a positive input fluctuation results in a negative output fluctuation (10 times larger). This configuration is known as a common-emitter amplifier with emitter degeneration.

