extrainfo:This represents a common-emitter amplifier circuit. Transistor Q1 amplifies the input signal. R1 and R2 create a voltage divider for biasing the transistor's base. RC is the collector resistor, and RE is the emitter resistor. C1 is a coupling capacitor that permits AC signals to pass while blocking DC.

Figure 2.34. Current source driving a resistor as load: an amplifier!

Figure 2.35. The blocking capacitor $C$ is selected to allow all relevant frequencies to pass through the high-pass filter formed with the parallel resistance of the base biasing resistors ${ }^{21}$; specifically,

$$
C \geq \frac{1}{2 \pi f\left(R_{1} \| R_{2}\right)}
$$

The quiescent collector current is 1.0 mA due to the applied base bias and the 1.0 k emitter resistor. This current sets the collector voltage at +10 volts $(+20 \mathrm{~V}$, minus 1.0 mA through 10k). Now, consider a small variation in the base voltage $v_{\mathrm{B}}$. The emitter voltage follows as $v_{\mathrm{E}}=v_{\mathrm{B}}$, leading to a variation in the emitter current:

$$
i_{\mathrm{E}}=v_{\mathrm{E}} / R_{\mathrm{E}}=v_{\mathrm{B}} / R_{\mathrm{E}}
$$

This results in a nearly identical change in the collector current (assuming a large $\beta$). Thus, the initial base voltage variation ultimately causes a collector voltage variation:

$$
v_{\mathrm{C}}=-i_{\mathrm{C}} R_{\mathrm{C}}=-v_{\mathrm{B}}\left(R_{\mathrm{C}} / R_{\mathrm{E}}\right)
$$

Eureka! It functions as a voltage amplifier, with a voltage gain defined by:

$$
\begin{equation*}
\text { gain }=v_{\text {out }} / v_{\mathrm{in}}=-R_{\mathrm{C}} / R_{\mathrm{E}} \tag{2.6}
\end{equation*}
$$

In this scenario, the gain is $-10,000 / 1000$, or -10. The negative sign indicates that a positive input variation results in a negative output variation (10 times larger). This configuration is known as a common-emitter amplifier with emitter degeneration.

#### A. Input and Output Impedances of the Common-Emitter Amplifier

Determining the input and output impedances of the amplifier is straightforward. The input signal encounters a parallel combination of 110k, 10k, and the impedance looking into the base. The latter is approximately:

