extrainfo:The circuit is a common-emitter amplifier with emitter degeneration. The input is at Vin, and the output is at Vout. It provides a gain of -10. The input impedance is roughly 8k ohms, and the output impedance is governed by RC. The circuit operates with a +20V supply voltage.

Figure 2.35. An AC common-emitter amplifier with emitter degeneration. Note that the output terminal is the collector, not the emitter.
about 100 k ( $\beta$ times $R_{\mathrm{E}}$ ), making the input impedance (primarily influenced by the 10k) around 8k. The input coupling capacitor thus forms a high-pass filter, with the 3 dB point at 200 Hz. The signal driving the amplifier perceives $0.1 \mu \mathrm{~F}$ in series with 8k, which, for typical frequencies (well above the 3 dB point), appears as 8k.

The output impedance is the parallel combination of 10k and the impedance looking into the collector. What is this impedance? If the collector resistor is removed, you are essentially looking into a current source. The collector impedance is very high (in the megohms), so the output impedance is effectively just the collector resistor, 10k. It is important to remember that the impedance looking into a transistor's collector is high, whereas the impedance looking into the emitter is low (as in an emitter follower). While the output impedance of a common-emitter amplifier is dominated by the collector load resistor, the output impedance of an emitter follower is not dominated by the emitter load resistor but rather by the impedance looking into the emitter.

Sometimes, it is beneficial to generate a signal and its inverse, meaning two signals that are $180^{\circ}$ out of phase. This can be easily achieved by using an emitter-degenerated amplifier with a gain of -1 (Figure 2.36). The quiescent collector voltage is set to $0.75 V_{\mathrm{CC}}$, instead of the typical $0.5 V_{\mathrm{CC}}$, to ensure the same outcomemaximum symmetrical output swing without clipping at either output. The collector can vary from $0.5 V_{\mathrm{CC}}$ to $V_{\mathrm{CC}}$, while the emitter can range from ground to $0.5 V_{\mathrm{CC}}$.

It is important to note that the phase-splitter outputs must be connected to equal (or very high) impedances at both outputs to preserve gain symmetry.
